\begin_layout Standard
This is the paper that develops the Health Deficit Model, so that there
 isn't any extensions of the theoretical framework.
 The main question 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dalgaardOptimalAgingDeath2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 answer in this paper is whether they can explain the Preston Curve using
 the Health Deficit Model assuming a causal link from income to longevity.
 The Preston Curve is the empirical regularity, that richer countries have
 healthier populations, but that the function from income to health is concave.
 This question is important because there isn't a scientific consensus of
 what creates the Preston Curve yet.
 The new theoretical concept is that health deterioates according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:law of motion of health capital"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The simple explanation for their model is that, if income increases, then
 because of diminishing marginal utility per period, the individual wants
 to smooth consumption, which she does by investing in health.
 The health investment then increases longevity.
 They calibrate their model using US data and compare it against an estimated
 Preston Curve.
 The estimated Preston Curve is concave, but close to linear, because of
 omission of childhood mortality (the HDM is only applicable from age 20).
 Of the parameters calibrated, the force of aging is set according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mitnitskiAccumulationDeficitsAge2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.043$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper improves upon previous research by evaluating the fit of the Preston
 Curve with a micro-founded model of health.
 They find that their calibrated model can explain 78% of the Preston Curve,
 and they argue, that the residual can be explained either by reverse causality
 or omitted variable bias.
\end_layout

